"# Appendix — The Verbs Cookbook

Entity-registry verbs — the small crew that manages the collection of live entities as a whole rather than one at a time. Every example verified against `bin/motoi eval`.

---

## Enumerate: `entity/all`

Returns the list of every live entity's id, in creation order. Nullary. Handy for iterating over the world when you need to do something to *every* entity — draw them all, tick them all, count them by kind.

```scheme
(entity/all)                                                     ; => ()
(begin (entity/make 'p1 10 20) (entity/all))                     ; => (\"p1\")
(begin (entity/make 'a 0 0) (entity/make 'b 10 10) (entity/all)) ; => (\"a\" \"b\")
```

Ids are strings. When you call `entity/spawn` (which auto-generates the id) they look like `\"e1\"`, `\"e2\"`; when you call `entity/make` (which takes an explicit id-as-symbol) they preserve the symbol's name as a string. Either way `entity/all` gives you back the strings.

---

## Scratch storage: `entity/ref`

Every entity carries a *scratch map* — a per-entity key/value store for whatever data you want to attach without extending the physics record. `entity/ref id key` reads a value; `entity/set!` (already in the base chapters) writes one. Missing keys return the special symbol `'nan` so a null return does not collide with a legitimate `#f` value.

```scheme
(begin (entity/make 'p1 10 20)
       (entity/set! 'p1 'hp 3)
       (entity/ref 'p1 'hp))
; => 3

(begin (entity/make 'p1 10 20)
       (entity/ref 'p1 'nothing))
; => nan
```

Use scratch for anything the built-in physics does not model — hit points, ammo counts, dialogue state, the entity's favourite colour. Anything a two-line game needs but the shared entity record should not.

---

## Removal: `entity/remove!`

Deletes an entity from the registry. Returns `#t` if the entity existed and got removed, `#f` if the id was already gone or never valid. `entity/remove!` is a *destructive* alias of `entity/despawn!` — same effect, shorter name for people who prefer the register/remove pairing.

```scheme
(begin (entity/make 'p1 10 20)
       (entity/remove! 'p1)
       (entity/all))
; => ()

(entity/remove! 'nonexistent)          ; => #f
```

After removal the id is free — a future `entity/make 'p1 ...` would create a fresh entity under the same name, with no state carried over from the removed one.

---

## Tag removal: `entity/untag!`

`entity/untag! id tag` removes a tag from an entity. Returns `#t` if the tag existed and got removed, `#f` if it was not present. Entities created via `entity/spawn` are auto-tagged with their kind, so you can un-tag them by kind name.

```scheme
(begin (entity/spawn 'hero)
       (entity/untag! \"e1\" 'hero))
; => #t

(entity/untag! \"never-existed\" 'anything)
; => #f
```

Use it when a stateful entity outgrows its group — the pickup that became a projectile, the enemy that turned friendly.

---

## Closing note

Every example in this appendix was checked against `bin/motoi eval` on 2026-07-17. Entity ids are strings once they land in the registry, regardless of whether they came in as symbols.
")
